  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The following proverb passes from the educator to the pupil:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "15 My son, if thine heart becometh wise,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "     My heart also in return will rejoice;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "16 And my reins will exult",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "     If thy lips speak right things.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Wisdom is inborn in no one. A true Arab. proverb says, \"The wise knows how the fool feels, for he himself was also once a fool;\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Note: The second part of the saying is, \"But a fool knows not how a wise man feels, for he has never been a wise man.\" I heard this many years ago, from the mouth of the American missionary Schaufler, in Constantinople.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and folly is bound up in the heart of a child, according to Proverbs 22:15, which must be driven out by severe discipline. 15b, as many others, cf. Proverbs 22:19, shows that these \"words of the wise\" are penetrated by the subjectivity of an author; the author means: if thy heart becomes wise, so will mine in return, i.e., corresponding to it (cf. גּם, Genesis 20:6), rejoice. The thought of the heart in Proverbs 23:15 repeats itself in Proverbs 23:16, with reference to the utterance of the mouth. Regarding מישׁרים, vid., Proverbs 1:5. Regarding the \"reins,\" כּליות (perhaps from כּלה, to languish, Job 19:21), with which the tender and inmost affections are connected, vid., Psychologie, p. 268f. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and folly is bound up in the heart of a child, according to ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 22:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", which must be driven out by severe discipline. 15b, as many others, cf. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 22:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", shows that these \"words of the wise\" are penetrated by the subjectivity of an author; the author means: if thy heart becomes wise, so will mine in return, i.e., corresponding to it (cf. גּם, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 20:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), rejoice. The thought of the heart in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 23:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
